### 🟡 Medium

**2. `sections/dba_control_room.py` — Triage view `priority_columns` references `SEVERITY`, `DOMAIN`, `ENTITY`, `DETAIL`, `NEXT_WORKFLOW`, `NEXT_ACTION` — but `_severity_rows()` returns `Severity`, `Signal`, `Evidence`, `Action`, `Route`, `Workflow` (mixed case, different names)**

```python
# In the Triage active_view block:
render_priority_dataframe(
    exceptions,
    priority_columns=[
        "SEVERITY", "DOMAIN", "SIGNAL", "ENTITY", "DETAIL",
        "NEXT_WORKFLOW", "NEXT_ACTION",
    ],
```

But `_severity_rows()` builds a DataFrame with columns `Severity`, `Signal`, `Evidence`, `Action`, `Route`, `Workflow` (title case). The `render_priority_dataframe` function filters to only show `priority_columns` that exist — so `SEVERITY`, `DOMAIN`, `ENTITY`, `DETAIL`, `NEXT_WORKFLOW`, `NEXT_ACTION` all silently produce empty columns. Only `SIGNAL` matches nothing either. The Triage view will render an effectively empty table even when exceptions exist.

**Fix:** Align the `priority_columns` list with the actual column names from `_severity_rows()`:
```python
priority_columns=["Severity", "Signal", "Evidence", "Action", "Route", "Workflow"],
```

